    "id": "polymarket_0x386813cf90074b5b5bc274d145be89a20f07386a3f8a7d370781a0af7196dc25",
    "title": "Will South Korean President Lee Jae-myung be impeached during 2025?",
    "question_type": "binary",
    "options": [
      "Yes",
      "No"
    ],
    "background": "No background available.",
    "resolution_criteria": "This market will resolve to \"Yes\" if the President of South Korea, Lee Jae-myung, is formally impeached by the South Korean National Assembly by December 31, 2025, 11:59 PM ET. Otherwise, this market will resolve to \"No.\"\n\nFor this market to resolve to \"Yes\" it is only necessary that the National Assembly propose and approve a motion of impeachment against Lee Jae-myung, regardless of whether the Constitutional Court later upholds the impeachment.\n\nThe primary resolution source for this market is official information from the South Korean government, however a consensus of credible reporting may be used.",
    "outcome": "No",
    "explanation": "\n# Executive Summary\nFollowing the chaotic removal of his predecessor Yoon Suk Yeol, Lee Jae-myung won the snap presidential election in June 2025. Despite facing ongoing legal challenges and opposition pressure, Lee managed to stabilize his administration and avoid impeachment. His strategic pivot toward centrist economic policies and emphasis on national unity caused his public approval to remain resilient, which ultimately resulted in the opposition lacking the political capital to mount a successful impeachment drive in 2025.\n\n# Timeline Of Key Events\n- December 2024: Predecessor Yoon Suk Yeol briefly attempts martial law, leading to his eventual ouster [art_general_20250427_011_cc58eb3c].\n- April 27, 2025: Lee Jae-myung is named the Democratic Party's candidate for the upcoming snap election [art_general_20250427_011_cc58eb3c].\n- June 2025: Lee Jae-myung wins the snap presidential election and assumes office.\n- Late 2025: Lee Jae-myung shifts to more business-friendly policies and manages relations with the US and China, solidifying his political standing [art_general_20251218_007_df596546].\n\n# Causal Chain Analysis\nThe failure to impeach Lee Jae-myung in 2025 was rooted in his strong electoral mandate following the political crisis of his predecessor [art_general_20250427_011_cc58eb3c]. This mandate caused the opposition to adopt a more cautious approach. Furthermore, Lee's strategic shift toward centrist economic policies led to sustained public support among moderate voters. Because his approval ratings remained stable, the opposition's efforts to capitalize on his ongoing legal trials failed to gain sufficient traction, which ultimately resulted in Lee surviving the year without facing a formal impeachment vote.\n\n# Countervailing Factors\nLee faced significant legal vulnerabilities, including ongoing trials for alleged election law violations and a property development scandal. These factors triggered continuous attacks from conservative opponents and created a plausible path for impeachment if a definitive court ruling had been issued against him during the year. However, these forces were overwhelmed by his strong party control and public desire for stability after the Yoon administration's collapse.\n\n# Event Candidate Inventory\n- E1: Lee Jae-myung named DP candidate\n  - Date: 2025-04-27\n  - Causally matters: Set him on the path to the presidency after Yoon's removal.\n  - Source: art_general_20250427_011_cc58eb3c\n- E2: Lee Jae-myung policy pivot\n  - Date: Mid-to-late 2025\n  - Causally matters: Strengthened his domestic position and shielded him from conservative attacks.\n  - Source: art_general_20251218_007_df596546\n\n# Evidence Mapping Table\n| Claim/Event | Article IDs | Date Support | Confidence (0-1) | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Lee named DP candidate | art_general_20250427_011_cc58eb3c | 2025-04-27 | 1.0 | Reuters report |\n| Diplomatic moves in late 2025 | art_general_20251218_007_df596546 | 2025-12-18 | 0.9 | Highlights stable governance |\n\n# Uncertainties And Alternative Paths\nThe most significant uncertainty was the timing of Supreme Court rulings on Lee's past legal issues. A definitive guilty verdict on his election law violation or property scandals could have provided an alternative causal path leading to his disqualification or impeachment.\n",
